{
  "texts": [
    "Since LLMs have been trained on large corpora of real-world text data, it is possible that some legal sources are present in the training data and therefore have previously been \"seen\" by the models, which the literature considers at length.",
    "4 As noted in some studies (Bommarito II and Katz 2022; Nay et al. 2023; Blair-Stanek et al. 2023), this represents a potential threat to the validity of research of this nature since a model may successfully complete a task simply by reproducing known material, rather than by \"interpreting\" its meaning.",
    "Bommarito II and Katz (2022) identified behavior which appeared to indicate that there were some legal sources in its training.",
    "In their research, Nay et al. (2023) and Blair-Stanek et al. (2023) specifically used synthetic cases to ensure the LLM had not been been trained on them.",
    "Notably, Blair-Stanek et al. (2023) found that GPT-3 was unlikely to have been trained on the complete U.S. tax code because it showed incorrect knowledge thereof."
  ]
}